<span class="name"><a name="94175"></a></span><span class="postdetails">#4:&nbsp;<font color=black><b></b> Author:&nbsp;<b>Hikaru</b>,&nbsp;</font></span><span class="postdetails"><font color=black></font></span>
<a href="viewtopic.php?p=94175#94175"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails"><font color=black>Posted: Thu Jan 20, 2005 7:26 pm</font><span class="gen"><br>
</td></tr>
<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody">When buying memory make sure you buy the right type of memory. I'd check to see how many RAM slots your motherboard has. If it has four and two of them are occupied then you can just buy a single stick of 512MB memory to bump your RAM up to 1GB. This will save you a bit of money but likely be lower performance than buying a 1GB RAM kit (2x512MB). If it only has two RAM slots you're better off buying a 1GB kit and then ebaying your old memory...but be aware that your used RAM will probably go for dirt cheap prices. 
<br />

<br />
There are better cards in that price range. I'd recommend an ATI 9600 Pro based video card. Check out <a href="http://www.newegg.com/app/ViewProductDesc.asp?description=14-125-166&depa=1" target="_blank" class="postlink"> GIGABYTE ATI RADEON 9600PRO Video Card, 256MB DDR</a> which is probably the best value in that price range that you specified. Or if you want to max out your $150 budget you can get the <a href="http://www.newegg.com/app/ViewProductDesc.asp?description=14-164-027&depa=1" target="_blank" class="postlink"> Rosewill ATI RADEON 9600XT Video Card, 256MB DDR.</a> The Rosewill is essentially the same card but with a higher core clock speed. It costs about $20 more and will bring slightly more performance but the Gigabyte card is the much better value. Both of these cards are much better than the one you specified.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
<br />
